When a small group of living beings (a small population) is separated from the main population from which it originated (for example, if it moves over a mountain range or a river, or if it moves to a new island so that it cannot easily go back), it often finds itself is often found in a different environment different from which it was before.
This new environment has different resources and competitors, so the new population will need new features or adaptations to be a powerful competitor to what it needed before.
The population of origin has not changed at all, but it still needs the same adaptations.
Over time as the new population adapts to its new environment, it begins to look less and less like the other population.
Finally, after thousands or even millions of years, the two populations will appear so different that they will no longer be considered to belong to the same species.
We call this “specific” process, which simply means the formation of new species. The speciation is an inevitable consequence and a very important part of the evolution.
